The `docker container prune` command is your cleanup crew for Docker ğŸ§¹â€”it removes **all stopped containers** from your system to free up space and reduce clutter.

---

### ğŸ§¾ What It Does

```bash
docker container prune
```

- Deletes **only stopped containers** (those that have exited or crashed).
- **Does not** touch running containers.
- Prompts for confirmation unless you use `--force`.

---

### ğŸ› ï¸ Common Options

| Option         | Description                                      |
|----------------|--------------------------------------------------|
| `--force`      | Skip confirmation prompt                         |
| `--filter`     | Remove containers based on conditions (e.g., age) |

Example with filter:
```bash
docker container prune --filter "until=24h"
```
Removes containers stopped more than 24 hours ago.

---

### âš ï¸ Warning

This command is irreversible. Once containers are pruned, their data is gone unless youâ€™ve mounted volumes externally.

---

Great question, Manish! Letâ€™s clear up the difference between `docker prune` and `docker rm`â€”they both remove things, but they work in very different ways ğŸ§¹ğŸ—‘ï¸

---

### ğŸ” `docker rm`: Manual Removal
- **Purpose**: Deletes specific containers that you name.
- **Usage**:
  ```bash
  docker rm <container_id_or_name>
  ```
- **Behavior**:
  - Only removes the containers you explicitly list.
  - Requires containers to be **stopped** first (unless you use `-f` to force).
  - Gives you **full control** over what gets deleted.

---

### ğŸ§¹ `docker container prune`: Automatic Cleanup
- **Purpose**: Removes **all stopped containers** in one go.
- **Usage**:
  ```bash
  docker container prune
  ```
- **Behavior**:
  - Deletes every container thatâ€™s not running.
  - Can be filtered by age or label.
  - Useful for **bulk cleanup** and reclaiming disk space.

---

### âš–ï¸ Key Differences

| Feature                  | `docker rm`                          | `docker container prune`                  |
|--------------------------|--------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------|
| Scope                    | Specific containers                  | All stopped containers                    |
| Control                  | Manual                               | Automatic                                 |
| Confirmation             | No prompt (unless scripted)          | Prompts unless `--force` is used          |
| Filtering                | Not supported                        | Supports `--filter` (e.g., by age)        |
| Risk of accidental loss | Low (you choose what to delete)      | Medium (deletes everything stopped)       |

---

### ğŸ¥ Visual Guides That Nail It

These videos explain the difference with real examples and demos:

1. [Docker! Pruning Images, Containers and More](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aWwloz_bfdI) â€” Breaks down how `prune` differs from `rm` and `rmi`, with practical use cases.
2. [Docker Quietly Eats Drives | Docker Prune & Cleanup Guide](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3Q0cVWR7RU4) â€” Shows how `prune` helps clean up disk space and compares it with manual removal.
3. [How To Remove All Stopped Containers And Unused Images ...](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LldNpfXDRJ4) â€” Demonstrates both `docker rm` and `docker container prune` side-by-side.
4. [Clean Up Unused Docker Containers, Images, Network ...](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wO8vmDUWNw4) â€” Covers how to clean up zombie containers and when to use each command.
5. [Docker tip: docker system prune and df](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_4QzP7uwtvI) â€” Explains how `docker system prune` expands on `container prune` to clean up everything.



The `docker stats` command is your real-time dashboard for monitoring container resource usage ğŸ“Š. It streams live metrics like CPU, memory, network, and disk I/O for running containersâ€”perfect for spotting performance bottlenecks or runaway processes.

---

### ğŸ§  What It Does

```bash
docker stats
```

- Displays a **live stream** of resource usage for all running containers.
- Shows metrics like:
  - **CPU %**: How much CPU each container is using.
  - **MEM USAGE / LIMIT**: Memory used vs. memory limit.
  - **MEM %**: Memory usage as a percentage.
  - **NET I/O**: Network traffic in/out.
  - **BLOCK I/O**: Disk read/write activity.
  - **PIDs**: Number of processes/threads.

---

### ğŸ› ï¸ Common Options

| Option            | Description                                                  |
|-------------------|--------------------------------------------------------------|
| `--no-stream`     | Show a one-time snapshot instead of continuous updates       |
| `--format`        | Customize output using Go templates                          |
| `--all`           | Include stopped containers (though they show zero usage)     |
| `--no-trunc`      | Prevent truncation of long output fields                     |

Example:
```bash
docker stats --no-stream --format "table {{.Name}}\t{{.CPUPerc}}\t{{.MemUsage}}"
```

---

### ğŸ¯ Target Specific Containers

You can monitor just one or a few containers:
```bash
docker stats my-nginx my-db
```

